body:
**Current state**: https://github.com/llvm/circt/pull/3244#issuecomment-1192360140

-----

This is a first step towards #2760: **Setup of the dialect**, but no import/export of the underlying scheduling problem yet. Happy to break this down into smaller PRs after the general discussion.

Quoting the rationale from the referenced issue:

> @mikeurbach and I think it would be useful to have an import/export format for scheduling problem instances, e.g. for writing test cases and benchmarking independent from the concrete (and potentially proprietary!) synthesis flow.
> 
> Going with the dialect approach (instead of just going with Cap'n'Proto, JSON, etc.) allows to generate Python bindings for the scheduling infrastructure with the usual mechanism. This would further benefit prototyping of new problem models and algorithms.
> 
> Note: The proposed dialect is intended for testing/prototyping/benchmarking purposes only! Synthesis flows are supposed to use the API provided by the Problem class hierarchy directly.

This PR defines the proposed IR to look like this:
```mlir
ssp.instance "canis14_fig2" of "ModuloProblem" {
  ssp.operator_type @MemPort {latency = 1, limit = 1}
  ssp.operator_type @Add {latency = 1}
  ssp.operator_type @Implicit {latency = 0}

  %0 = ssp.operation @load_A(@store_A {distance = 1}) {opr = @MemPort, startTime = 2}
  %1 = ssp.operation @load_B() {opr = @MemPort, startTime = 0}
  %2 = ssp.operation @add(%0, %1) {opr = @Add, startTime = 3}
  ssp.operation @store_A(%2) {opr = @MemPort, startTime = 4}
  ssp.operation @last(@store_A) {opr = @Implicit, startTime = 5}
} {initiationInterval = 3}
```

The above example would replace the following test case, where especially the encoding of auxiliary dependence edges and their properties is kind of awkward:
```mlir
func.func @canis14_fig2() attributes {
  problemInitiationInterval = 3,
  auxdeps = [ [3,0,1], [3,4] ],
  operatortypes = [
    { name = "mem_port", latency = 1, limit = 1 },
    { name = "add", latency = 1 }
  ] } {
  %0 = "dummy.load_A"() { opr = "mem_port", problemStartTime = 2 } : () -> i32
  %1 = "dummy.load_B"() { opr = "mem_port", problemStartTime = 0 } : () -> i32
  %2 = arith.addi %0, %1 { opr = "add", problemStartTime = 3 } : i32
  "dummy.store_A"(%2) { opr = "mem_port", problemStartTime = 4 } : (i32) -> ()
  return { problemStartTime = 5 }
}
```
